  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "(Φόρμις/Phórmis) or Phormus (Φόρμος/Phórmos in Ath. 14,652a
    Them. Or. 27 p. 337b, Suda ε 2766, φ 609 = [1. test. 1]). P. was a Syracusan, and like his contemporary Epicharmus,
    a poet of comic dramas, allegedly also tutor to the sons of the tyrant Gelon..." Nesselrath, Heinz-Günther (Göttingen). "
    Phormis." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2009. Brill Online
    . Tufts University Library.</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 3, 1867, p. 346: "Phormis or Phormus, ....
    He came originally from Maenalus in Arcadia, and having removed to Sicily, became intimate with Gelon...There seems
    to be little or no doubt that this is the same person who is associated by Aristotle with Epicharmus as one of 
    the originators of comedy, or of a particular form of it..."</mads:note>
